      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey, my tomato plants are acting weird. the leaves on the bottom of the stems are turning this sickly yellow color but the top ones look okay. what's probably going on and how do i fix the soil?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yellowing leaves on the bottom of your tomato plants, while the top ones are still green, is a classic sign of a nutrient deficiency, often related to nitrogen or potassium, which is a common problem when the soil is not properly managed. You might be dealing with a nitrogen deficiency, which is like a hungry, low-grade green-hued pest infestation on a grand scale. To fix the soil, you'll want to amend it with a balanced, slow-release organic fertilizer, or perhaps a liquid feed rich in nitrogen, applied according to the package directions. Also, ensure your soil has good drainage; soggy soil is just as bad as dry soil for these poor plants.",
