      "content": "Checking the pH is smart; you don't want to treat the soil like a giant, poorly managed mud pit that the poor little root systems can't navigate. The most straightforward way to check the pH is to use a simple soil testing kit, which you can buy at any garden center. These kits usually involve mixing a small sample of your soil with a specific solution and then comparing the resulting color to a chart. Alternatively, if you want the most accurate reading, you can send a sample to a local agricultural extension office, but that takes longer than waiting for a batch of fresh, slightly-too-acidic, slightly-too-alkaline *goblins* to wander into your garden. Remember, the ideal pH for tomatoes is usually between 6.0 and 6.8.",
